Package org.ASUX.yaml

Class YAMLPath

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.ASUX.yaml.YAMLPath
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable
    public class YAMLPath
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.io.Serializable
    This class encapsulates a YAML Path/Pattern, and makes it super-easy to parse and manipulate it. In fact, this class makes it very safe to assume that the user's input (for the YAMLPath/pattern) is valid and squeaky-clean. That is, you should expect minimal run-time errors.

    A YAML Path (also referred to as: YAML Path-Pattern) is composed of one or more Path-ELEMENT-Patterns separated by "delimiter" (like period/dot/".")

    If you'd like to use delimiters other than period/dot/"." then you'll be foreced to write Java-code, as commandline does Not support any other delimiter (for now).

    Here are rules for YAML Path Pattern

    1. Except for the 2nd rule (below) all RegExp symbols(like '+' or "[{]} as defined and supported by java.util.regex) it'll work - guaranteed!

    2. Important - there is ONLY 1 deviation/substitution: Whenever a star/asterisk/'*' with a delimiter on either side (that is, the Path-ELEMENT is = exactly star/asterisk/'+').. .. is detected, it is automatically replaced with ".*"

      This substitution is allowed ONLY for human convenience.

    3. Any other use of RegExp compatible star/asterisk/'*' (example: paths./pet*.{get|put|post}.responses.200) will be used as is - to match YAML elements.
    4. Note: ** (double star/asterisk/"*") implies unlimited-match prefix. It's a Special case: "**" represents a deviation of java.util.regexp specs on what qualifies as a regular-expression. This deviation is a very human-friendly easy-2-understand need.

    Example: paths.*.*.responses.200". ATTENTION: This is a human readable pattern, NOT a 100% proper RegExp-pattern

    Example: paths./pet*.{get|put|post}.responses.200. ATTENTION: This is 100% proper RegExp-pattern

        public YAMLPath​(java.lang.String _yp)

        Constructor takes a YAML Path like paths./pet.put.consumes

        It breaks it up into regexpressions separated by the default DELIMITER = "."

        Special case: "**" represents a deviation of java.util.regexp specs on what qualifies as a regular-expression. This deviation is a very human-friendly easy-2-understand need.

        Parameters:
        _yp - example: "paths.*.*.responses.200" where the delimiter is fixed to be the period/dot "." - - ATTENTION: This is a human readable pattern, NOT a proper RegExp-pattern

      • hasNext

        public boolean hasNext()
        For example strings like "paths.*.*.responses.200", your first call will return true. If you call next() up to 4 times, this function will return true. After you call next() a 5th time, this function will return false.
        Returns:
        true means get() will return a valid string, GUARANTEED to NOT Throw any runtime exception :-)

      • next

        public void next()
        For example strings like "paths.*.*.responses.200", your 1st 5 invocations will make this object point to valid Path-Elements (call get() to get those valid Path-Element-strings. After you call next() a 6th time (for same example), this object will point to null(String) and from then onwards, get() will return null.

      • get

        public java.lang.String get()
        For example strings like "paths.*.*.responses.200", after your first call to next(), this will return "paths". For the 2nd call to next(), this function will return "*". After you call next() a 5th time(or more), this function will return null(String).
        Returns:
        a string that does NOT have periods/dots/delimiter in it. The string may be (based on example above) = "*".

      • index

        public int index()
        For example strings like "paths.*.*.responses.200", your first call will return 0 (index numbering per C/Java array-index standard). Every call to next() will increment the return value of this function. When you call next() a 5th/6th/7th/../100th time for above example, this function will return the same value then onwards (= # of elements in the YAMLPath-string. In this example, that is 5)
        Returns:
        integer >= 0 (if things are working) and -1 is things are screwed up.

      • getPrefix

        public java.lang.String getPrefix()
        For example strings like "paths.*.*.responses.200", before your 1st call to next(), this function will return ""(empty string). After the 1st call to next(), this function will return "paths". After the 2nd call to next(), this will return "paths.*". After you call next() a 5th time (or more), this function will return "paths.*.*.responses.200".
        Returns:
        a string that does NOT have periods/dots in it. The string may be (based on example above) = "*".

      • hasWildcardPrefix

        public boolean hasWildcardPrefix()
        For example: strings like "**.xml", before your 1st call to next(), this function will return true. After the 1st call to next(), this function will return "true". After the 2nd call .., this will return false
        Returns:
        whether the previous YAML-Element was "**" or Not.

      • getSuffix

        public java.lang.String getSuffix()
        For example strings like "paths.*.*.responses.200", before your 1st call to next(), this function will return "paths.*.*.responses.200". After the 1st call to next(), this function will return "*.*.responses.200". After the 3rd call to next(), this will return "responses.200". After you call next() a 5th time(or more), this function will return null(String).
        Returns:
        a string that does NOT have periods/dots in it. The string may be (based on example above) = "*".
